RBAC (6:11 - 6:45)

RBAC in kubernetes
Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) is the native authorization framework in Kubernetes that regulates who can perform 
specific actions on resources within a cluster. It operates on a purely additive model, meaning there are no "deny" rules; if an action is
not explicitly permitted, it is blocked by default.

The Core Pillars of RBACKubernetes RBAC determines access by evaluating three factors: Who (Subjects) is attempting to do What (Verbs) to
Which resource (API Objects).

[ SUBJECT ]  ──────────►  [ BINDING ]  ──────────►  [ ROLE ]  ──────────►  [ RESOURCE ]
(User/ServiceAccount)    (RoleBinding/ClusterBinding)     (Rules & Verbs)        (Pods/Secrets)

1. Subjects (Who)The entities requesting access to the Kubernetes API server:

Users: Human accounts managed outside Kubernetes via external systems like OIDC or SSL certificates.
Groups: Collections of users categorized externally (e.g., Azure AD or Okta groups).
ServiceAccounts: Internal accounts managed by Kubernetes for software workloads running inside Pods.

2. API Resources and Verbs (What & Where)

Resources: Objects exposed by the API server, such as pods, services, secrets, or deployments.
Verbs: The permitted actions on those resources, such as get, list, watch, create, update, patch, or delete.

The Four Core RBAC ObjectsKubernetes splits authorization manifests into namespaced (restricted to one sandbox) and cluster-scoped 
(spanning the entire environment) objects.

Object                      Scope                        Function
Role                        Namespaced                   Defines a list of allowed resources and verbs inside a specific namespace.
ClusterRole                 Cluster-wide                 Defines rules for cluster-scoped objects (like Nodes) or global permissions across all namespaces.
RoleBinding                 Namespaced                   Grants permissions of a Role (or a ClusterRole restricted to that namespace) to subjects.
ClusterRoleBinding          Cluster-wide                 Grants permissions of a ClusterRole to subjects across every namespace globally.

Cluster Upgrade 
Upgrading a Kubernetes cluster must be performed sequentially minor-version-by-minor-version (e.g., v1.34 to v1.35, then v1.35 to v1.36). 
You cannot skip minor versions. The core upgrade workflow always requires updating the Control Plane first, followed by the worker nodes, 
and finally the cluster add-ons and clients.

