working on EC2 instance)
Kubernetes monitoring and logging are essential practices for maintaining application uptime, tracking resource usage, and debugging system
errors. Monitoring tracks quantitative metrics like CPU and memory utilization, while logging captures the discrete, chronological events
generated by your applications and cluster components.

Kubernetes Monitoring Architecture
Monitoring a Kubernetes cluster requires collecting metrics at both the infrastructure (node) level and the workload (pod) level.

Metric Server: A cluster-wide aggregator of resource usage data. It provides metrics for core commands like kubectl top and powers the 
Horizontal Pod Autoscaler (HPA).
Prometheus: The industry standard for Kubernetes monitoring. It scrapes metrics from endpoints, stores time-series data, and triggers 
alerts via Alertmanager.
Grafana: A visualization platform often paired with Prometheus to build rich, real-time dashboards for cluster health.
Kube-State-Metrics: A service that listens to the Kubernetes API server and generates metrics about the state of objects, such as 
deployment replicas and pod statuses.

